Creating a 3D render of a hologram-like character named "handyc" that responds to user inputs requires a combination of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Below is a simple example of how you can create a web app that simulates this concept using basic 3D rendering with CSS and JavaScript. 

This example uses a simple 3D cube to represent the hologram, and it responds to user inputs through a text box. For a more advanced 3D rendering, you would typically use libraries like Three.js, but for simplicity, this example will keep it basic.

Here's the complete code in a single HTML file:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Handyc Hologram</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            height: 100vh;
            background-color: #282c34;
            color: white;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }
        #hologram {
            width: 100px;
            height: 100px;
            background-color: rgba(0, 255, 255, 0.7);
            transform-style: preserve-3d;
            animation: rotate 5s infinite linear;
            position: relative;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }
        @keyframes rotate {
            from {
                transform: rotateY(0deg);
            }
            to {
                transform: rotateY(360deg);
            }
        }
        #inputArea {
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
        }
        #userInput {
            padding: 10px;
            font-size: 16px;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
        }
        #response {
            padding: 10px;
            background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.1);
            border-radius: 5px;
            width: 300px;
            text-align: center;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <div id="hologram"></div>
    <div id="inputArea">
        <input type="text" id="userInput" placeholder="Type something for Handyc..." />
        <button id="submitBtn">Send</button>
        <div id="response"></div>
    </div>

    <script>
        const responses = {
            "hello": "Hello! I'm Handyc, your holographic assistant!",
            "how are you?": "I'm just a hologram, but I'm doing great! How about you?",
            "what can you do?": "I can respond to your questions and have a chat with you!",
            "bye": "Goodbye! Have a great day!",
        };

        document.getElementById('submitBtn').addEventListener('click', function() {
            const userInput = document.getElementById('userInput').value.toLowerCase();
            const responseDiv = document.getElementById('response');

            if (responses[userInput]) {
                responseDiv.textContent = responses[userInput];
            } else {
                responseDiv.textContent = "I'm not sure how to respond to that.";
            }

            document.getElementById('userInput').value = ''; // Clear input
        });
    </script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML Structure**: The HTML consists of a `div` for the hologram, an input area for user interaction, and a response area to display Handyc's replies.
- **CSS Styles**: The CSS styles create a simple rotating cube effect to simulate a hologram. The background and text colors are set for better visibility.
- **JavaScript Functionality**: The JavaScript listens for button clicks, checks the user input against predefined responses, and displays the appropriate response.

### Usage:
1. Copy the code into a text editor and save it as `index.html`.
2. Open the file in a web browser to interact with the hologram "Handyc".

This is a basic implementation. For a more realistic hologram effect, consider using WebGL or libraries like Three.js for 3D rendering.

To create a more realistic 3D character with limbs using a 3D rendering library, we can use Three.js, which is a popular library for rendering 3D graphics in the browser. Below is an example of a simple web app that creates a 3D humanoid figure and allows user interaction.

This example will include a basic 3D model of a person using Three.js, along with embedded CSS and JavaScript in a single HTML file.

Here's the complete code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Handyc Hologram</title>
    <style>
        body {
            margin: 0;
            overflow: hidden;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #282c34;
            color: white;
        }
        #inputArea {
            position: absolute;
            top: 20px;
            left: 20px;
            z-index: 10;
        }
        #userInput {
            padding: 10px;
            font-size: 16px;
            margin-right: 10px;
        }
        #response {
            margin-top: 10px;
            background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.1);
            border-radius: 5px;
            padding: 10px;
            width: 300px;
            text-align: center;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <div id="inputArea">
        <input type="text" id="userInput" placeholder="Type something for Handyc..." />
        <button id="submitBtn">Send</button>
        <div id="response"></div>
    </div>

    <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/three.js/r128/three.min.js"></script>
    <script>
        let scene, camera, renderer, handyc;

        function init() {
            // Create scene
            scene = new THREE.Scene();
            camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(75, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000);
            renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer({ alpha: true });
            renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
            document.body.appendChild(renderer.domElement);

            // Create a simple humanoid figure
            const geometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry(1, 2, 0.5); // Body
            const material = new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial({ color: 0x00ffff });
            handyc = new THREE.Mesh(geometry, material);
            scene.add(handyc);

            // Create limbs
            const limbMaterial = new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial({ color: 0x00ffff });
            const armGeometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry(0.5, 1, 0.5); // Arms
            const legGeometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry(0.5, 1.5, 0.5); // Legs

            const leftArm = new THREE.Mesh(armGeometry, limbMaterial);
            leftArm.position.set(-1, 0, 0);
            handyc.add(leftArm);

            const rightArm = new THREE.Mesh(armGeometry, limbMaterial);
            rightArm.position.set(1, 0, 0);
            handyc.add(rightArm);

            const leftLeg = new THREE.Mesh(legGeometry, limbMaterial);
            leftLeg.position.set(-0.5, -2, 0);
            handyc.add(leftLeg);

            const rightLeg = new THREE.Mesh(legGeometry, limbMaterial);
            rightLeg.position.set(0.5, -2, 0);
            handyc.add(rightLeg);

            camera.position.z = 5;

            animate();
        }

        function animate() {
            requestAnimationFrame(animate);
            handyc.rotation.y += 0.01; // Rotate the character
            renderer.render(scene, camera);
        }

        const responses = {
            "hello": "Hello! I'm Handyc, your holographic assistant!",
            "how are you?": "I'm just a hologram, but I'm doing great! How about you?",
            "what can you do?": "I can respond to your questions and have a chat with you!",
            "bye": "Goodbye! Have a great day!",
        };

        document.getElementById('submitBtn').addEventListener('click', function() {
            const userInput = document.getElementById('userInput').value.toLowerCase();
            const responseDiv = document.getElementById('response');

            if (responses[userInput]) {
                responseDiv.textContent = responses[userInput];
            } else {
                responseDiv.textContent = "I'm not sure how to respond to that.";
            }

            document.getElementById('userInput').value = ''; // Clear input
        });

        window.addEventListener('resize', function() {
            camera.aspect = window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight;
            camera.updateProjectionMatrix();
            renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
        });

        init();
    </script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **Three.js Library**: The code includes the Three.js library from a CDN to handle 3D rendering.
- **3D Model**: A simple humanoid figure is created using box geometries for the body and limbs. The figure rotates continuously to simulate a holographic effect.
- **User Interaction**: The input area allows users to type messages, and the app responds based on predefined responses.
- **Responsive Design**: The canvas resizes when the window is resized to maintain the aspect ratio.

### Usage:
1. Copy the code into a text editor and save it as `index.html`.
2. Open the file in a web browser to interact with the 3D character "Handyc".

This example provides a basic 3D humanoid figure. For more complex models, you would typically use 3D modeling software to create and export models in formats like GLTF or OBJ, which can then be loaded into Three.js.

